commit.message:
add function rbtx_cleanup

Currently we have rbtx_init, but not a corresponding
clean up function. Add this rbtx_cleanup function to
clean up resources allocated in the init part.

Close the FDs upon FIN from client

Seen in the customer environment that once packet's checksum validation
gets failed by server, client sends FIN to close the connection. But
since there were refcounts on transport due to the back channels to client
server do not respond with an FIN-ACK. Hence client thinks that the old
session is intact and do not reestablish the connection. After the default
120s of lease expiry, once the client is notified of expiry by sending FIN
from server, client tries to reclaim old locks & states with the old
session and gets errors.

This CR fixes the above issue by closing the FDs upon FIN from client.
xprt structure cleanup continues to happen along with the existing client
expiry, which kicks in after the lease expiry.

Signed-off-by: Rojin George <itsmerojin@gmail.com>

commit.message:
svc_vc: Introduce flag to not create new xprt on lookup

Until now, given a FD, svc_fd_ncreatef API looks-up or
creates a xprt. The xprt creation may not be always desired.
For example, clnt_vc_ncreate_svc API operates on an existing
xprt, and it does not want svc_fd_ncreatef to create a
new xprt even if the existing xprt gets removed from the
global xprt-tree at the time of lookup.

svc_vc: During connection closure, reset FD after freeing xprt's user-data

When terminating a xprt connection, the connection is first closed,
the corresponding FD is then reset, and the xprt's user-data is then
freed. This CL changes the sequence of the last two operations to
reset the connection FD only after the xprt's user-data is first
freed. This allows performing operations on xprt's user-data that
rely on the xprt FD. A sample operation could be to resolve some
connection-specific user-data that is referenced by the xprt FD.
As part of the connection termination, this data needs to be first
resolved and then released.

clnt_vc: Add function to get rpc_client's service-xprt handle

When an rpc_client handle is created for a connection, the
connection's transport handle's reference is maintained within
the client duplex-receiver. This CL adds a function to return
this transport handle for a given rpc_client.

One of the applications of this function is to check if an
rpc_client used by the caller, has its transport handle being
destroyed.

Add callback support for un-referencing xprt user-data before destroy

When destroying an svc-xprt object, the references (to and from it)
held through its user-data fields must be released. Such unreleased
references to the svc-xprt object would otherwise not allow it to be
completely destroyed, resulting in leakage. Additionally, the
unreleased references to other data held by this svc-xprt object
would prevent that data to correctly use the svc-xprt due to it being
under-destruction.

This CL adds support for registering a callback function that would
perform the above un-referencing. This function would then be called
during destruction of an svc-xprt object.

Additionally, this CL also updates the existing `svc_destroy_it`
function (that is, the `SVC_DESTROY` macro) to call the above added
callback function.

commit.message:
worker pool threads, enable setting an appropriate thread stack size

glibc's default thread stack size is 8M. N.B. This can be overridden
across the whole process by setting the stack size with ulimit; by default
threads will inherit the same size for their thread stack. w

Empirical testing shows that, e.g., ganesha works fine with ntirpc using
a thread stack size as small 32K. (At 16K, NFSv4 mounts fail; the stack
underflows.)

commit.message:
Implement HA Proxy V2 Protocol

On TCP connections, if we receive an HA Proxy V2 header, we will replace
xp_remote with the address provided in the header. The original address
will have been copied to xp_proxy which will allow the upper layer
(nfs-ganesha for example) to validate that HA Proxy is allowed from that
host. This allows a server to protect itself from spoofing by unauthorized
proxies.

Attempting the do the validation in ntirpc resulted in the client endlessly
retrying the connection.

Signed-off-by: Frank S. Filz <ffilzlnx@mindspring.com>

commit.message:
ntirpc: use __THROW attribute in {set,end}rpcent

Modern glibc headers use the __THROW attribute for setrpcent and
endrpcent. When compiled against C++ code, the absence of this attribute
in ntirpc code causes compilation error due to declarations mismatch
("has a different exception specifier").

Signed-off-by: Shachar Sharon <ssharon@redhat.com>
